     234             : /*
     235             :    Flags/methods for returning states.
     236             : 
     237             :    The SWIG conversion methods, as ConvertPtr, return an integer
     238             :    that tells if the conversion was successful or not. And if not,
     239             :    an error code can be returned (see swigerrors.swg for the codes).
     240             : 
     241             :    Use the following macros/flags to set or process the returning
     242             :    states.
     243             : 
     244             :    In old versions of SWIG, code such as the following was usually written:
     245             : 
     246             :      if (SWIG_ConvertPtr(obj,vptr,ty.flags) != -1) {
     247             :        // success code
     248             :      } else {
     249             :        //fail code
     250             :      }
     251             : 
     252             :    Now you can be more explicit:
     253             : 
     254             :     int res = SWIG_ConvertPtr(obj,vptr,ty.flags);
     255             :     if (SWIG_IsOK(res)) {
     256             :       // success code
     257             :     } else {
     258             :       // fail code
     259             :     }
     260             : 
     261             :    which is the same really, but now you can also do
     262             : 
     263             :     Type *ptr;
     264             :     int res = SWIG_ConvertPtr(obj,(void **)(&ptr),ty.flags);
     265             :     if (SWIG_IsOK(res)) {
     266             :       // success code
     267             :       if (SWIG_IsNewObj(res) {
     268             :         ...
     269             :   delete *ptr;

     273             :     } else {
     274             :       // fail code
     275             :     }
     276             : 
     277             :    I.e., now SWIG_ConvertPtr can return new objects and you can
     278             :    identify the case and take care of the deallocation. Of course that
     279             :    also requires SWIG_ConvertPtr to return new result values, such as

   21489             : #endif
   21490             : /* -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   21491             :  * Type initialization:
   21492             :  * This problem is tough by the requirement that no dynamic
   21493             :  * memory is used. Also, since swig_type_info structures store pointers to
   21494             :  * swig_cast_info structures and swig_cast_info structures store pointers back
   21495             :  * to swig_type_info structures, we need some lookup code at initialization.
   21496             :  * The idea is that swig generates all the structures that are needed.
   21497             :  * The runtime then collects these partially filled structures.
   21498             :  * The SWIG_InitializeModule function takes these initial arrays out of
   21499             :  * swig_module, and does all the lookup, filling in the swig_module.types
   21500             :  * array with the correct data and linking the correct swig_cast_info
   21501             :  * structures together.
   21502             :  *
   21503             :  * The generated swig_type_info structures are assigned statically to an initial
   21504             :  * array. We just loop through that array, and handle each type individually.
   21505             :  * First we lookup if this type has been already loaded, and if so, use the
   21506             :  * loaded structure instead of the generated one. Then we have to fill in the
   21507             :  * cast linked list. The cast data is initially stored in something like a
   21508             :  * two-dimensional array. Each row corresponds to a type (there are the same
   21509             :  * number of rows as there are in the swig_type_initial array). Each entry in
   21510             :  * a column is one of the swig_cast_info structures for that type.
   21511             :  * The cast_initial array is actually an array of arrays, because each row has
   21512             :  * a variable number of columns. So to actually build the cast linked list,
   21513             :  * we find the array of casts associated with the type, and loop through it
   21514             :  * adding the casts to the list. The one last trick we need to do is making
   21515             :  * sure the type pointer in the swig_cast_info struct is correct.
   21516             :  *
   21517             :  * First off, we lookup the cast->type name to see if it is already loaded.
   21518             :  * There are three cases to handle:
   21519             :  *  1) If the cast->type has already been loaded AND the type we are adding
   21520             :  *     casting info to has not been loaded (it is in this module), THEN we
   21521             :  *     replace the cast->type pointer with the type pointer that has already
   21522             :  *     been loaded.
   21523             :  *  2) If BOTH types (the one we are adding casting info to, and the
   21524             :  *     cast->type) are loaded, THEN the cast info has already been loaded by
   21525             :  *     the previous module so we just ignore it.
   21526             :  *  3) Finally, if cast->type has not already been loaded, then we add that
   21527             :  *     swig_cast_info to the linked list (because the cast->type) pointer will
   21528             :  *     be correct.
   21529             :  * ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
   21530             : 
   21531             : #ifdef __cplusplus
   21532             : extern "C" {
   21533             : #if 0
   21534             : } /* c-mode */
   21535             : #endif
   21536             : #endif
